      <Fragment slot="intro">
        <p>You do not need a fancy setup to nail AeroPress timing. That is part of the appeal. Still, a few basic tools make the whole process feel less like guessing and more like following a recipe you can trust.</p>
      </Fragment>
      <p>The biggest one is a burr grinder. Burr means the coffee gets broken into more even pieces instead of random dust and boulders. When the grounds are more even, brew time actually means something. If the grind is a mess, you can steep for the exact same number every morning and still get wildly different cups. If you want help there, read our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind-size.html">best AeroPress grind size guide</a>.</p>
      <p>A scale matters too. Not because you need to become a coffee monk, but because it is hard to figure out brew time if the coffee dose keeps wobbling around from cup to cup. If your ratios feel slippery, our <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a> clears that up fast.</p>
      <Callout variant="tip" title="Keep your timing honest">
