  <Fragment slot="steps">
    <section>
      <h2 id="steps">Step-by-step: how long should you brew AeroPress?</h2>

      <h3>1. Start with a forgiving recipe before you get clever</h3>
      <p>Use 15 grams of coffee and 240 grams of water. That is the sweet spot I would hand most people without overthinking it. It gives you enough body to feel satisfying, but it still leaves room for the cup to taste lively instead of heavy.</p>
      <p>Grind medium-fine. Think table salt. Not fluffy like powder. Not chunky like crushed pepper. If you are coming from a blade grinder, this change alone can feel like cleaning a foggy window. Suddenly the cup has shape.</p>

      <h3>2. Pour hot water, but do not obsess over the exact degree</h3>
      <p>Aim for 185 to 195°F. That is hot enough to pull plenty of flavor, but not so hot that darker beans turn bitter and papery. If you mostly drink lighter roasts, lean toward the hotter end. If you like chocolatey medium-dark beans, lean cooler. Our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brew-temp.html">best AeroPress brew temp guide</a> goes deeper on that part.</p>
      <p>What matters here is consistency. Pick a rough temperature range and stay there for a few brews. That way, when the cup changes, you know the timing or grind did it instead of some random kettle swing.</p>

      <h3>3. Wet the grounds first, then start the main steep</h3>
      <p>Add just enough water to soak all the coffee, give it a gentle stir or swirl, then pour the rest up to your full water weight. This little first pour helps the bed brew more evenly. You are not chasing some fancy ritual here. You are just making sure dry pockets are not hiding in the coffee.</p>
      <p>Once the full pour is in, let the AeroPress sit until you hit about 75 to 90 seconds total contact time. That range is the best starting point for balanced flavor. It is long enough to build sweetness and body, but short enough that the cup still tastes fresh.</p>

      <h3>4. Press slowly for about 20 to 30 seconds</h3>
      <p>You want steady pressure, not a dramatic body slam. A smooth press usually gives a smoother cup. If the plunger feels like it is fighting you, that is often the grind telling you it is too fine. Listen to it.</p>
      <p>Stop at the hiss. You can force the last bit through if you want, but that final push often tastes rougher than it is worth. The cleaner move is to stop, pour, and taste.</p>

      <h3>5. Change time only when the cup gives you a clear signal</h3>
      <p>This is where people make AeroPress harder than it needs to be. If the cup tastes sour, your first fix is usually a finer grind or a little more time. If it tastes bitter, go a little coarser or cut the steep shorter. If it tastes weak but not sour, add more coffee before you start stretching brew time into next week.</p>
      <p>Extraction just means how much flavor the water pulls out of the grounds. Too little and the cup tastes sharp, thin, or lemony. Too much and it gets bitter, dry, and kind of woody. Brew time sits right in the middle of that tug-of-war.</p>

      <h3>6. Use a bypass recipe if you want more strength without the mud</h3>
      <p>If your goal is a stronger cup, do not automatically keep steeping longer. That is how you end up with bitterness instead of strength. A bypass brew is the smarter move. Brew a smaller concentrate first, then dilute after pressing until it tastes right.</p>
      <p>Try 18 grams of coffee with 120 to 140 grams of water, steep around 60 to 75 seconds, then add hot water after the press. You get more punch, but the cup stays cleaner and easier to control.</p>

