  <Fragment slot="common-mistakes">
    <section>
      <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common mistakes</h2>

      <h3>Letting it sit forever because longer feels safer</h3>
      <p>This one sounds logical, but it backfires a lot. Longer brew times do not just add flavor. They can also drag out the harsh stuff. If your cup already tastes balanced at 80 seconds, pushing it to two minutes may just make it dull and bitter.</p>

      <h3>Changing grind, water, dose, and time all at once</h3>
      <p>That is like trying to season soup by dumping in salt, vinegar, sugar, and pepper at the same time. Even if it gets better, you will not know why. Change one thing. Taste. Then decide.</p>

      <h3>Pressing too hard</h3>
      <p>If you are leaning your whole body into the AeroPress, something is off. Usually the grind is too fine, or you stirred too aggressively and packed the bed tight. A slow press should feel controlled, not violent.</p>

      <h3>Using old filters or skipping cleanup</h3>
      <p>Paper filters are cheap, and stale oils taste stale. If the cup suddenly tastes tired and flat, your brew time may not be the real problem. Sometimes the gear just needs a quick refresh. If cleanup has turned into a chore, our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-filters.html">best AeroPress filters guide</a> can help you pick the setup you will actually use.</p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="troubleshooting">
    <section>
      <h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting by taste</h2>
      <p>The easiest way to fix AeroPress timing is to read the cup like a clue. If it tastes sour, think underdone. If it tastes bitter, think overdone. If it tastes weak but smooth, think ratio first.</p>
      <p><strong>Sour or sharp:</strong> steep 10 seconds longer, or grind a little finer. <strong>Bitter or dry:</strong> cut 10 seconds off, or go a touch coarser. <strong>Weak but pleasant:</strong> add more coffee or try a bypass brew. Those changes are small, but that is the point. Small moves are easier to trust.</p>
      <p>One more thing people miss: filter choice changes how timing tastes. Paper filters usually make the cup cleaner and brighter, so small timing shifts show up more clearly. If you are chasing the clearest possible cup, our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-filters.html">best AeroPress filters guide</a> is worth reading right after this one.</p>

